## Hermes Agent role

Hermes is the runtime that gives your agents tools, memory, profiles, skills, gateways, cron jobs, and MCP integrations.

It is the execution shell for the system, not the whole company by itself. Galyarder-style company architecture sits above Hermes; Hermes supplies the hands, runtime, profile isolation, gateway surfaces, and automation primitives.

## Official install paths

Prefer official Hermes install paths instead of hand-rolled cloning unless you are contributing to Hermes itself.

### Linux, macOS, or WSL2

Use the official installer:

```bash
curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/main/scripts/install.sh | bash
hermes postinstall
hermes --version
```

Or install through Python packaging when that is the chosen route:

```bash
pip install hermes-agent
hermes postinstall
hermes --version
```

`hermes postinstall` matters because it installs or checks runtime dependencies such as Node.js/browser/media helpers that are easy to miss when the CLI itself appears installed.

### Windows

Windows native support may exist, but treat it as early-beta until verified on the target machine. For builder-grade setups, use WSL2 first so shell, browser tooling, Python, Node.js, cron-like scripts, and file permissions behave predictably.

## First setup wizard

After install, configure the runtime interactively:

```bash
hermes setup
hermes setup model
hermes model
```

Use `hermes model` when changing provider/model later. The model must support stable tool calling and a context window appropriate for the job.

## Model gate

For an Owner/Operator/agentic-company core profile, require at least a **64K token context window**.

Recommended gate:

| Use | Minimum context | Notes |
|---|---:|---|
| Support profile | 64K | Needs memory, state, and careful tone. |
| Operator layer | 64K | Needs principles, plan, tools, verification, and active files. |
| Workforce specialist | 32K–64K | Smaller is acceptable only for narrow tasks. |
| Tiny utility worker | task-specific | Must not own broad decisions. |

If a model cannot reliably call tools, read long context, and preserve instructions, do not use it as the core Operator.

## Install and verify

After setup, verify the basics:

```bash
hermes --version
hermes doctor
hermes status --all
hermes tools list
hermes --profile default chat -q "who are you?"
```

Minimum checks:

- the CLI launches;
- model provider is configured;
- terminal/file/web tools are visible;
- memory backend is not crashing;
- profile path is what you expect;
- `hermes doctor` does not show unresolved critical failures.

If diagnostics fail, run:

```bash
hermes doctor --fix
hermes config check
hermes config migrate
```

Then rerun the verification commands. Do not call the runtime ready from config presence alone.

## Config and env management

Use Hermes CLI for config discovery and routine edits:

```bash
hermes config
hermes config path
hermes config env-path
hermes config set <key> <value>
hermes config check
hermes config migrate
```

Use:

- `config.yaml` for non-secret settings;
- `.env` for API keys and provider secrets;
- private credential registry for account metadata;
- OS keychain/password manager when available;
- profile distributions for clean non-secret profile packages.

Never put raw tokens, passwords, cookies, TOTP secrets, backup codes, private keys, or session dumps into profile instructions, skills, Obsidian, memory, docs, or git.

## Profile layout

Recommended structure:

```text
~/.hermes/
  config.yaml              # global/default config
  .env                     # local secrets only, never publish
  profiles/
    companion/
      profile instructions.md / profile.md
      config.yaml
      memories/
    operator/
      profile instructions.md / profile.md
      config.yaml
      skills/
      memories/
```

Keep secrets out of this visible structure unless the file is explicitly private, local-only, permission-restricted, and excluded from backups/public repos.

Profile verification:

```bash
hermes --profile companion chat -q "who are you and what must you ask before doing?"
hermes --profile operator chat -q "who are you and what must you verify before saying done?"
```

A profile is not verified unless the command uses the explicit `--profile <name>` flag.

## Toolsets

Start minimal:

- file tools;
- terminal;
- web search/extract;
- browser only when needed;
- memory;
- cron/background process;
- MCP only after the core profile works.

Useful commands:

```bash
hermes tools
hermes tools list
hermes tools enable <toolset>
hermes tools disable <toolset>
```

Tool rule:

> If an answer depends on live file/system/source state, use a tool. Memory is not proof.

## Skills

Skills are reusable procedures. They are not personality decorations.

Use skills for:

- Hermes setup;
- Paperclip operation;
- Discord routing;
- Google Workspace;
- platform operators;
- browser/session workflows;
- deployment;
- design/copy/code review;
- verification.

Useful commands:

```bash
hermes skills list
hermes skills search <query>
hermes skills install <skill-id-or-url>
hermes skills inspect <skill-id-or-url>
hermes skills check
hermes skills update
hermes skills config
```

Create or update a skill when a workflow took several steps, overcame errors, or will recur. Do not store secrets or raw private session logs in skills.

## MCP integrations

MCP is for structured external systems: docs, issue trackers, note systems, control planes, and custom APIs.

Useful commands:

```bash
hermes mcp add <name> --url <server-url>
hermes mcp add <name> --command <stdio-command>
hermes mcp list
hermes mcp status
hermes mcp login <name>
hermes mcp remove <name>
```

Remote hosted MCP servers that use OAuth should be configured with OAuth auth and then logged in:

```yaml
auth: oauth
```

```bash
hermes mcp login notion
hermes mcp login linear
hermes mcp status
```

Common MCP operating risk:

- `401` from a hosted MCP usually means OAuth/login is missing or expired, not necessarily that the server is down.
- tool listed ≠ authenticated;
- OAuth success ≠ downstream API readiness;
- MCP call works ≠ side effect is approved.

## Gateways

Gateways let the agent operate from Discord, Telegram, email, or other channels.

Set up through Hermes instead of editing platform code by hand:

```bash
hermes setup gateway
hermes gateway setup
hermes gateway status
```

Gateway setup must define:

- trusted human allowlist;
- whether bot-authored messages are accepted;
- mention requirement;
- delivery target;
- toolsets enabled in the gateway;
- restart/reload procedure;
- directed smoke test.

Gateway logs should be checked when routing fails:

```bash
# common path
~/.hermes/logs/gateway.log
```

A gateway is not ready just because the process is running. Verify a real message round-trip from the intended platform/channel.

## Cron and background work

Use cron for recurring jobs:

- daily company pulse;
- weekly stale task audit;
- memory review;
- cost review;
- service health check.

Cron prompts must be self-contained because future runs do not inherit chat context.

Useful in-chat cron shape:

```text
/cron add "Every weekday 08:20 WIB, send a concise company ops pulse..."
```

Important cron options/concepts:

- `deliver`: where the output goes;
- `script`: data collection before the agent reasons;
- `no_agent`: script-only watchdog mode;
- `workdir`: project-specific execution context;
- `context_from`: chain previous job output;
- repeat count/schedule: one-shot vs recurring.

Do not create recursive cron jobs that schedule more cron jobs.

## Delegation

Use subagents for isolated work or parallel research, but verify their reports. A subagent saying `done` is not proof.

Verification examples:

- read the file it claims it wrote;
- run the test it claims passed;
- fetch the URL it claims deployed;
- inspect the issue/approval it claims created.

## Sessions, checkpoints, and rollback

Use sessions and checkpoints for large edits or risky refactors:

```bash
hermes sessions browse
hermes chat --checkpoints
```

Inside a checkpoint-enabled session, use rollback only after reading the proposed rollback target:

```text
/rollback
```

Checkpoints are not a replacement for git, tests, or backups. They are an extra guardrail.

## Updates and support bundles

Before updating a production-like setup:

```bash
hermes update --check
```

Then backup config/profile state, update, and verify:

```bash
hermes update
hermes doctor
hermes status --all
```

For support/debugging, Hermes may provide dump/export commands such as:

```bash
hermes dump
```

Treat support bundles as sensitive even when logs are redacted. Review before sharing. Never publish raw tokens, cookies, private memories, sessions, account recovery files, or disaster-recovery archives.

## Profile distribution

A clean profile distribution can include:

- profile instructions;
- skills;
- scripts;
- hooks;
- public docs;
- curated non-secret memories if intentionally approved.

It must exclude:

- `.env`;
- auth tokens;
- cookies;
- private credential registry;
- raw sessions;
- raw memory DBs;
- logs;
- caches;
- browser state;
- wallet keys;
- disaster recovery archives.
